WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:10.000
Chapter 7, in which kanga and baby ru come to the forest, and piglet has a bath.

00:10.000 --> 00:17.000
Nobody seemed to know where they came from, but there they were in the forest, kanga and baby ru.

00:17.000 --> 00:22.000
When Pu asked Christopher Robin, how did they come here, Christopher Robin said,

00:22.000 --> 00:29.000
in the usual way, if you know what I mean, Pu, and Pu, who didn't, said, oh.

00:29.000 --> 00:36.000
Then he nodded his head twice and said, in the usual way, ah.

00:36.000 --> 00:40.000
Then he went a call upon his friend piglet to see what he thought about it,

00:40.000 --> 00:46.000
and at Piglet's house he found rabbit, so they all talked about it together.

00:46.000 --> 00:49.000
What I don't like about it is this, said rabbit.

00:49.000 --> 00:56.000
Here are we, you Pu, and you piglet, and me, and suddenly, and Ior, said Pu,

00:56.000 --> 01:03.000
and Ior, and then suddenly, and Ior, said Pu, and Ior, and then all of a sudden,

01:03.000 --> 01:08.000
oh, and Ior, said Pu, I was forgetting him.

01:08.000 --> 01:20.000
Here we are, said rabbit, slowly and carefully, all of us, and then suddenly we wake up one morning

01:20.000 --> 01:21.000
and what do we find?

01:21.000 --> 01:26.000
We find a strange animal among us, an animal of whom we had never even heard before,

01:26.000 --> 01:31.000
an animal who carries her family about with her in her pocket.

01:31.000 --> 01:37.000
Suppose I carried my family about with me in my pocket, how many pockets should I want?

01:37.000 --> 01:39.000
Sixteen, said piglet.

01:39.000 --> 01:44.000
Seventeen, isn't it, said rabbit, and one more for a handkerchief that's eighteen,

01:44.000 --> 01:48.000
eighteen pockets in one suit, I haven't time.

01:48.000 --> 01:54.000
There was a long and thoughtful silence, and then Pu, who had been frowning very hard

01:54.000 --> 01:59.000
for some minutes, said, I make it fifteen.

01:59.000 --> 02:05.000
What, said rabbit, fifteen, fifteen, what?

02:05.000 --> 02:08.000
Your family, what about them?

02:08.000 --> 02:14.000
Pu rubbed his nose and said that he thought rabbit had been talking about his family.

02:14.000 --> 02:17.000
Did I, said rabbit, carelessly?

02:17.000 --> 02:22.000
Yes, you said, never mind Pu, said piglet impatiently.

02:22.000 --> 02:25.000
The question is, what are we going to do about kanga?

02:25.000 --> 02:29.000
Oh, I see, said Pu.

02:29.000 --> 02:35.000
The best way, said rabbit, would be this, the best way would be to steal baby Roo and hide him,

02:35.000 --> 02:42.000
and then when kanga says, where's baby Roo, we say, aha!

02:42.000 --> 02:45.000
Aha, said Pu, practicing.

02:45.000 --> 02:50.000
Aha, aha, of course, he went on.

02:50.000 --> 02:55.000
We could say aha, even if we hadn't stolen baby Roo.

02:55.000 --> 03:00.000
Pu, said rabbit kindly, you haven't any brain?

03:00.000 --> 03:02.000
I know, said Pu humbly.

03:02.000 --> 03:08.000
We say aha, so that kanga knows that we know where baby Roo is.

03:08.000 --> 03:14.000
Aha means we'll tell you where baby Roo is if you promise to go away from the forest and never come back.

03:14.000 --> 03:17.000
Now, don't talk while I think.

03:17.000 --> 03:22.000
Pu went into a corner and tried saying aha in that sort of voice.

03:22.000 --> 03:28.000
Sometimes it seemed to him that it did mean what rabbit said, and sometimes it seemed to him that it didn't.

03:28.000 --> 03:31.000
I suppose it's just practice, he thought.

03:31.000 --> 03:37.000
I wonder if kanga will have to practice too, so as to understand it.

03:37.000 --> 03:42.000
There's just one thing, said piglet, fidgeting a bit.

03:42.000 --> 03:51.000
I was talking to Christopher Robin and he said that a kanga was generally regarded as one of the fiercer animals.

03:51.000 --> 04:00.000
I'm not frightened of fiercer animals in the ordinary way, but it is well known that a one of the fiercer animals is deprived of its young.

04:00.000 --> 04:10.000
It becomes as fiercer as two of the fiercer animals, in which case aha is perhaps a foolish thing to say.

04:12.000 --> 04:16.000
Piglet, said rabbit, taking out a pencil and licking the end of it.

04:16.000 --> 04:18.000
You haven't any pluck.

04:18.000 --> 04:27.000
It is hard to be brave, said piglet, sniffing slightly, when you're only a very small animal.

04:27.000 --> 04:31.000
Rabbit, who had begun to write very busily, looked up and said,

04:31.000 --> 04:37.000
it is because you are a very small animal that you will be useful in the adventure before us.

04:37.000 --> 04:43.000
Piglet was so excited at the idea of being useful that he forgot to be frightened anymore,

04:43.000 --> 04:47.000
and when rabbit went on to say that kangas were only fierce during the winter months,

04:47.000 --> 04:52.000
being at other times of an affectionate disposition, he could hardly sit still.

04:52.000 --> 04:56.000
He was so eager to begin being useful at once.

04:56.000 --> 05:02.000
What about me, said poo, sadly? I suppose I shan't be useful.

05:02.000 --> 05:05.000
Never mind poo, said piglet comfortably.

05:05.000 --> 05:07.000
Another time, perhaps.

05:07.000 --> 05:14.000
Without poo, said rabbit, solemnly as he sharpened his pencil, the adventure would be impossible.

05:14.000 --> 05:19.000
Ha! said piglet, and tried not to look disappointed.

05:19.000 --> 05:23.000
But poo went into a corner of the room and said proudly to himself,

05:23.000 --> 05:29.000
impossible without me, that sort of bear.

05:29.000 --> 05:33.000
Now listen, all of you, said rabbit, when he'd finished writing,

05:33.000 --> 05:37.000
and poo and piglet sat listening very eagerly with their mouths open.

05:37.000 --> 05:41.000
This was what rabbit read out.

05:41.000 --> 05:45.000
Plan to capture baby Roo.

05:45.000 --> 05:47.000
One, general remarks.

05:47.000 --> 05:51.000
Kanga runs faster than any of us even me.

05:51.000 --> 05:54.000
Two, more general remarks.

05:54.000 --> 06:01.000
Kanga never takes her eye off baby Roo, except when he's safely buttoned up in her pocket.

06:01.000 --> 06:03.000
Three, therefore.

06:03.000 --> 06:07.000
If we are to capture baby Roo, we must get a long start,

06:07.000 --> 06:11.000
because Kanga runs faster than any of us even me.

06:11.000 --> 06:12.000
See one.

06:12.000 --> 06:15.000
Four, a thought.

06:15.000 --> 06:20.000
If Roo had jumped out of Kanga's pocket and piglet had jumped in,

06:20.000 --> 06:25.000
Kanga wouldn't know the difference, because piglet is a very small animal.

06:25.000 --> 06:27.000
Five, like Roo.

06:27.000 --> 06:31.000
Six, but Kanga would have to be looking the other way first,

06:31.000 --> 06:35.000
so as not to see piglet jumping in.

06:35.000 --> 06:37.000
Seven, see two.

06:37.000 --> 06:39.000
Eight, another thought.

06:39.000 --> 06:44.000
But if Pooh was talking to her very excitedly,

06:44.000 --> 06:47.000
she might look the other way for a moment.

06:47.000 --> 06:50.000
Nine, and then I could run away with Roo.

06:50.000 --> 06:52.000
Ten, quickly.

06:52.000 --> 06:56.000
Eleven, and Kanga wouldn't discover the difference until afterwards.

06:57.000 --> 07:00.000
Well, Rabbit read this out proudly,

07:00.000 --> 07:04.000
and for a little while after he'd read it, nobody said anything.

07:04.000 --> 07:08.000
And then piglet, who'd be opening and shutting his mouth without making any noise,

07:08.000 --> 07:11.000
managed to say very huskily.

07:11.000 --> 07:14.000
And afterwards.

07:14.000 --> 07:16.000
How do you mean?

07:16.000 --> 07:20.000
When Kanga does discover the difference,

07:20.000 --> 07:23.000
then we all say, aha!

07:23.000 --> 07:25.000
All three of us?

07:25.000 --> 07:27.000
Yes.

07:27.000 --> 07:28.000
Huh.

07:28.000 --> 07:30.000
Why, what's the trouble, piglet?

07:30.000 --> 07:31.000
Nothing.

07:31.000 --> 07:32.000
Said piglet.

07:32.000 --> 07:35.000
As long as we all three say it.

07:35.000 --> 07:37.000
As long as we all three say it.

07:37.000 --> 07:38.000
Said piglet.

07:38.000 --> 07:39.000
I don't mind.

07:39.000 --> 07:41.000
He said.

07:41.000 --> 07:45.000
But I shouldn't care to say aha by myself.

07:45.000 --> 07:48.000
It wouldn't sound nearly so well.

07:48.000 --> 07:49.000
Either way.

07:49.000 --> 07:50.000
He said.

07:50.000 --> 07:54.000
You are quite sure about what you said about the winter months.

07:54.000 --> 07:56.000
The winter months?

07:56.000 --> 07:57.000
Yes.

07:57.000 --> 07:58.000
Only being fierce.

07:58.000 --> 08:00.000
In the winter months.

08:00.000 --> 08:01.000
Oh, yes.

08:01.000 --> 08:02.000
Yes.

08:02.000 --> 08:03.000
That's all right.

08:03.000 --> 08:05.000
Well, Poo, you see what you have to do?

08:05.000 --> 08:06.000
No.

08:06.000 --> 08:07.000
Said Poo Bear.

08:07.000 --> 08:09.000
Not yet, he said.

08:09.000 --> 08:11.000
What do I do?

08:11.000 --> 08:16.000
Well, you just have to talk very hard to Kanga so she doesn't notice anything.

08:16.000 --> 08:17.000
Oh.

08:17.000 --> 08:18.000
What about?

08:18.000 --> 08:20.000
Anything you like?

08:21.000 --> 08:24.000
You mean like telling her a little bit of poetry or something?

08:24.000 --> 08:25.000
That's it.

08:25.000 --> 08:26.000
Said rabbit.

08:26.000 --> 08:27.000
Splendid.

08:27.000 --> 08:28.000
No.

08:28.000 --> 08:29.000
Come along.

08:29.000 --> 08:33.000
So they all went out to look for Kanga.

08:33.000 --> 08:39.000
Kanga and Roo were spending a quiet afternoon in a sandy part of the forest.

08:39.000 --> 08:44.000
Baby Roo was practicing very small jumps in the sand and falling down mouse holes and climbing out of them.

08:44.000 --> 08:49.000
And Kanga was fidgeting about and saying, just one more jump there and then we must go home.

08:49.000 --> 08:54.000
And at that moment, who should come stumping up the hill but Poo?

08:54.000 --> 08:56.000
Good afternoon, Kanga.

08:56.000 --> 08:58.000
Good afternoon, Poo.

08:58.000 --> 09:00.000
Look at me jumping.

09:00.000 --> 09:04.000
Sweet Roo and fell into another mouse hole.

09:04.000 --> 09:06.000
Hello, Roo, my little fellow.

09:06.000 --> 09:08.000
We were just going home.

09:08.000 --> 09:09.000
Said Kanga.

09:09.000 --> 09:10.000
Good afternoon, rabbit.

09:10.000 --> 09:12.000
Good afternoon, piglet.

09:12.000 --> 09:18.000
Rabbit and piglet who had now come up from the other side of the hill said, good afternoon and hello, Roo.

09:18.000 --> 09:21.000
And Roo asked them to look at him jumping.

09:21.000 --> 09:23.000
So they stayed and looked.

09:23.000 --> 09:25.000
And Kanga looked too.

09:25.000 --> 09:27.000
Oh, Kanga.

09:27.000 --> 09:28.000
Said Poo.

09:28.000 --> 09:31.000
After rabbit had winked at him twice.

09:31.000 --> 09:35.000
I don't know if you are interested in poetry at all.

09:35.000 --> 09:37.000
Hardly at all.

09:37.000 --> 09:38.000
Said Kanga.

09:38.000 --> 09:40.000
Oh, said Poo.

09:40.000 --> 09:44.000
Roo dear, just one more jump and then we must go home.

09:44.000 --> 09:49.000
There was a short silence while Roo fell down another mouse hole.

09:49.000 --> 09:54.000
Go on, said rabbit, and a loud whisper behind his paw.

09:54.000 --> 10:01.000
And talking of poetry, said Poo, I made up a little piece as I was coming along.

10:01.000 --> 10:03.000
It went like this.

10:03.000 --> 10:04.000
Let me see.

10:04.000 --> 10:06.000
Fancy, said Kanga.

10:06.000 --> 10:10.000
Now, Roo dear, you'll like this piece of poetry, said rabbit.

10:10.000 --> 10:12.000
You love it.

10:12.000 --> 10:13.000
Said piglet.

10:13.000 --> 10:18.000
You must listen very carefully, said rabbit, so as not to miss any of it.

10:18.000 --> 10:19.000
Said piglet.

10:19.000 --> 10:21.000
Oh, yeah, said Kanga.

10:21.000 --> 10:24.000
But she still looked at baby Roo.

10:24.000 --> 10:27.000
How did it go, Poo?

10:27.000 --> 10:29.000
Said rabbit.

10:29.000 --> 10:33.000
Poo gave a little cough and began.

10:34.000 --> 10:39.000
Lines written by a bear of very little brain.

10:39.000 --> 10:44.000
On Monday when the sun is hot, I wonder to myself a lot.

10:44.000 --> 10:47.000
Now is it true or is it not?

10:47.000 --> 10:50.000
That what is which and which is what?

10:50.000 --> 10:56.000
On Tuesday when it hails and snows, the feeling on me grows and grows.

10:56.000 --> 11:02.000
That hardly anybody knows if those are these or these are those.

11:03.000 --> 11:08.000
On Wednesday when the sky is blue and I have nothing else to do,

11:08.000 --> 11:14.000
I sometimes wonder if it's true that who is what and what is who.

11:14.000 --> 11:20.000
On Thursday when it starts to freeze and whore frost twinkles on the trees,

11:20.000 --> 11:24.000
how very readily one sees that these are who's.

11:24.000 --> 11:26.000
But who's are these?

11:26.000 --> 11:28.000
On Friday.

11:28.000 --> 11:30.000
Yes it is, isn't it?

11:30.000 --> 11:31.000
Said Kanga.

11:31.000 --> 11:33.000
Not waiting to hear what happened on Friday.

11:33.000 --> 11:37.000
Just one more jump road here, then we really must be going.

11:37.000 --> 11:40.000
Rabbit gave Poo a hurrying up sort of nudge.

11:40.000 --> 11:44.000
The talking of poetry, said Poo quickly.

11:44.000 --> 11:49.000
Have you ever noticed that tree right over there?

11:49.000 --> 11:50.000
Where?

11:50.000 --> 11:51.000
Said Kanga.

11:51.000 --> 11:54.000
Now Roo, right over there.

11:54.000 --> 11:57.000
Said Poo, pointing behind Kanga's back.

11:57.000 --> 11:58.000
No.

11:58.000 --> 11:59.000
Said Kanga.

11:59.000 --> 12:01.000
Now jump in Roo-Dian with her home.

12:01.000 --> 12:04.000
You ought to look at that tree right over there.

12:04.000 --> 12:06.000
Said Rabbit, shall I lift you in Roo?

12:06.000 --> 12:08.000
He picked up Roo in his paws.

12:08.000 --> 12:10.000
I can see a bird in it from here.

12:10.000 --> 12:13.000
Said Poo, or is it a fish?

12:13.000 --> 12:15.000
You ought to see that bird from here.

12:15.000 --> 12:17.000
Said Rabbit, unless it is a fish.

12:17.000 --> 12:19.000
It isn't a fish, it's a bird.

12:19.000 --> 12:20.000
Said Piglet.

12:20.000 --> 12:22.000
So it is, said Rabbit.

12:22.000 --> 12:24.000
Is it a starling or a black bird?

12:24.000 --> 12:26.000
Said Poo, that's the whole question.

12:26.000 --> 12:29.000
Said Rabbit, is it a black bird or a starling?

12:29.000 --> 12:34.000
And then, at last, Kanga did turn her head to look.

12:34.000 --> 12:38.000
And the moment that her head was turned, Rabbit said in a loud voice,

12:38.000 --> 12:40.000
In you go, Roo.

12:40.000 --> 12:43.000
And in jumped Piglet into Kanga's pocket.

12:43.000 --> 12:49.000
And off-scampered Rabbit with Roo in his paws as fast as he could.

12:49.000 --> 12:51.000
Why, where's Rabbit?

12:51.000 --> 12:53.000
Said Kanga, turning around again.

12:53.000 --> 12:55.000
Are you all right, Roo-Dian?

12:55.000 --> 13:00.000
Piglet made a squeaky Roo noise from the bottom of Kanga's pocket.

13:00.000 --> 13:04.000
Rabbit had to go away, said Poo.

13:04.000 --> 13:08.000
I think he thought of something he had to go and see about, suddenly.

13:08.000 --> 13:10.000
And Piglet?

13:10.000 --> 13:15.000
I think Piglet thought of something at the same time, suddenly.

13:15.000 --> 13:17.000
Well, we must be getting home, said Kanga.

13:17.000 --> 13:19.000
Goodbye, Poo.

13:19.000 --> 13:24.000
And in three large jumps, she was gone.

13:24.000 --> 13:27.000
Poo looked after her, she went.

13:27.000 --> 13:30.000
I wish I could jump like that, he thought.

13:30.000 --> 13:34.000
Some can, and some can't.

13:34.000 --> 13:36.000
That's how it is.

13:36.000 --> 13:40.000
But there were moments when Piglet wished that Kanga couldn't.

13:40.000 --> 13:44.000
Often, when he'd had a long walk home through the forest, he'd wished that he were a bird,

13:44.000 --> 13:48.000
but now he thought jerkily to himself at the bottom of Kanga's pocket,

13:48.000 --> 13:54.000
if this is flying, I shall never really take to it.

13:54.000 --> 13:56.000
And as he went up in the air, he said,

13:56.000 --> 13:58.000
Ooooooh.

13:58.000 --> 13:59.000
And as he came down, he said,

13:59.000 --> 14:00.000
Ahhh.

14:00.000 --> 14:01.000
And he was saying,

14:01.000 --> 14:03.000
Ooooooh.

14:03.000 --> 14:04.000
Ahhh.

14:04.000 --> 14:05.000
Ahhh.

14:05.000 --> 14:06.000
Ahhh.

14:06.000 --> 14:07.000
Ahhh.

14:07.000 --> 14:08.000
Ahhh.

14:08.000 --> 14:09.000
Ahhh.

14:09.000 --> 14:11.000
All the way to Kanga's house.

14:11.000 --> 14:17.000
Of course, as soon as Kanga unbuttoned her pocket, she saw what had happened.

14:17.000 --> 14:20.000
Just for a moment, she thought she was frightened.

14:20.000 --> 14:26.000
And then she knew she wasn't, for she felt sure that Christopher Robin would never let any harm happen to Roo.

14:26.000 --> 14:28.000
So she said to herself,

14:28.000 --> 14:34.000
If they are having a joke with me, I will have a joke with them.

14:34.000 --> 14:36.000
Now then, Roo dear.

14:36.000 --> 14:39.000
She said as she took Piglet out of her pocket.

14:39.000 --> 14:40.000
Bet time.

14:40.000 --> 14:42.000
Ahhh.

14:42.000 --> 14:43.000
Said Piglet.

14:43.000 --> 14:45.000
As well as he could after his terrifying journey.

14:45.000 --> 14:50.000
But it wasn't a very good aha, and Kanga didn't seem to understand what it meant.

14:50.000 --> 14:53.000
Bath first said Kanga in a cheerful voice.

14:53.000 --> 14:55.000
Ahhh.

14:55.000 --> 14:59.000
Said Piglet again, looking round anxiously for the others, but the others weren't there.

14:59.000 --> 15:02.000
Rabbit was playing with Baby Roo in his own house,

15:02.000 --> 15:04.000
and feeling more fond of him every minute.

15:04.000 --> 15:11.000
And Poo, who had decided to be a Kanga, was still at the sandy place on the top of the forest, practicing jumps.

15:11.000 --> 15:20.000
I'm not at all sure, said Kanga, in a thoughtful voice, that it wouldn't be a good idea to have a cold bath this evening.

15:20.000 --> 15:22.000
Would you like that Roo dear?

15:22.000 --> 15:32.000
Piglet, who had never been really fond of Bath's, shuttered a long, indignant shutter, and said in as brave a voice as he could.

15:32.000 --> 15:34.000
Kanga?

15:34.000 --> 15:38.000
I see that the time has come to speak plainly.

15:38.000 --> 15:43.000
Funny little Roo, said Kanga, as she got the bath water ready.

15:43.000 --> 15:46.000
I am not Roo, said Piglet loudly.

15:46.000 --> 15:48.000
I'm Piglet!

15:48.000 --> 15:56.000
Yes dear, yes, said Kanga soothingly, and imitating Piglet's voice too, so clever of him.

15:56.000 --> 16:00.000
She went on and she took a large bar of yellow soap out of the cupboard.

16:00.000 --> 16:02.000
What will he be doing next?

16:02.000 --> 16:03.000
Can't you sing?

16:03.000 --> 16:07.000
Shouted Piglet, having you come in the eyes, look at me!

16:07.000 --> 16:13.000
I am looking Roo dear, said Kanga rather severely, and you know what I told you yesterday about making faces.

16:13.000 --> 16:20.000
If you go on making faces like Piglet's, you will grow up to look like Piglet and then think how sorry you'll be.

16:20.000 --> 16:26.000
Now then, into the bath and don't let me have to speak to you about it again.

16:26.000 --> 16:34.000
Before he knew where he was, Piglet was in the bath, and Kanga was scrubbing him firmly with a large, lathery flannel.

16:34.000 --> 16:36.000
Ah-how!

16:36.000 --> 16:37.000
Quite Piglet!

16:37.000 --> 16:39.000
Let me out on Piglet!

16:39.000 --> 16:42.000
Don't happen the mouth dear, or the soap goes in, said Kanga.

16:42.000 --> 16:44.000
There, what did I tell you?

16:44.000 --> 16:48.000
You did it on purpose!

16:48.000 --> 16:54.000
Spluttered Piglet as soon as he could speak again, and then accidentally had another mouth full of lathery flannel.

16:54.000 --> 16:58.000
That's right dear, don't say anything, said Kanga.

16:58.000 --> 17:03.000
And, in another minute, Piglet was out of the bath and being rubbed dry with a towel.

17:03.000 --> 17:08.000
Now, said Kanga, there she metzen, and then bed.

17:08.000 --> 17:10.000
Well, what metzen?

17:10.000 --> 17:12.000
Said Piglet.

17:12.000 --> 17:18.000
To make you grow big and strung dear, you don't want to grow up small and weak like Piglet, do you?

17:18.000 --> 17:20.000
Well then.

17:20.000 --> 17:23.000
At that moment, there was a knock at the door.

17:23.000 --> 17:25.000
Come in, said Kanga.

17:25.000 --> 17:27.000
And in came Christopher Robin.

17:27.000 --> 17:30.000
Christopher Robin, Christopher Robin!

17:30.000 --> 17:32.000
Clyde Piglet, tell Kanga who I am!

17:32.000 --> 17:36.000
She keeps saying, I'm Rue, I'm not Rue, am I?

17:36.000 --> 17:41.000
Christopher Robin looked at him very carefully and shook his head.

17:41.000 --> 17:44.000
You can't be Rue, he said.

17:44.000 --> 17:48.000
Because I've just seen Rue playing in Rabbit's house.

17:48.000 --> 17:51.000
Well, said Kanga.

17:51.000 --> 17:53.000
Fancy that.

17:53.000 --> 17:56.000
Fancy my making a mistake like that.

17:56.000 --> 17:57.000
There you are!

17:57.000 --> 17:58.000
Said Piglet.

17:58.000 --> 18:01.000
I told you so, I'm Piglet!

18:01.000 --> 18:04.000
Christopher Robin shook his head again.

18:04.000 --> 18:06.000
Oh, you're not Piglet.

18:06.000 --> 18:09.000
He said, I know Piglet well.

18:09.000 --> 18:12.000
And he's quite a different colour.

18:12.000 --> 18:17.000
Piglet began to say that this was because he had just had a bath.

18:17.000 --> 18:20.000
And then he thought that perhaps he wouldn't say that.

18:20.000 --> 18:26.000
And as he opened his mouth to say something else, Kanga slipped the medicine spoon in.

18:26.000 --> 18:32.000
And then patted him on the back and told him that it was really quite a nice taste when you got used to it.

18:32.000 --> 18:35.000
I knew it wasn't Piglet, said Kanga.

18:35.000 --> 18:38.000
I wonder who it can be.

18:38.000 --> 18:43.000
Perhaps it's some relation of poos, said Christopher Robin.

18:43.000 --> 18:47.000
But a nephew or an uncle or something.

18:47.000 --> 18:54.000
Kanga agreed that this was probably what it was and said that they would have to call it by some name.

18:54.000 --> 19:02.000
I shall call it Poodle, said Christopher Robin, Henry Poodle for short.

19:02.000 --> 19:07.000
And just when he was decided, Henry Poodle wriggled out of Kanga's arms and jumped to the ground.

19:07.000 --> 19:11.000
To his great joy, Christopher Robin had left the door open.

19:11.000 --> 19:16.000
He never had Henry Poodle Piglet run so fast as he ran then.

19:16.000 --> 19:21.000
And he didn't stop running until he got quite close to his house.

19:21.000 --> 19:27.000
But when he was 100 yards away, he stopped running and rolled the rest of the way home.

19:27.000 --> 19:32.000
So as to get his own nice, comfortable colour again.

19:32.000 --> 19:36.000
So Kanga and Ru stayed in the forest.

19:36.000 --> 19:41.000
And every Tuesday Ru spent the day with his great friend Rabbit.

19:41.000 --> 19:48.000
And every Tuesday Kanga spent the day with her great friend Poo, teaching him to jump.

19:48.000 --> 19:54.000
And every Tuesday Piglet spent the day with his great friend Christopher Robin.

19:54.000 --> 19:59.000
So they were all happy again.

20:00.000 --> 20:07.000
Chapter 8, in which Christopher Robin leads an expedition to the North Pole.

20:09.000 --> 20:13.000
One fine day, Poo had stumped up to the top of the forest.

20:13.000 --> 20:17.000
To see of his friend Christopher Robin was interested in bears at all.

20:17.000 --> 20:22.000
At breakfast that morning, a simple meal of marmalade spread lightly over a honeycomb or two.

20:22.000 --> 20:25.000
He had suddenly thought of a new song.

20:25.000 --> 20:27.000
It began like this.

20:28.000 --> 20:32.000
Sing ho for the life of a bear.

20:32.000 --> 20:37.000
When you've got as far as this, he scratched his head and thought to himself,

20:37.000 --> 20:42.000
that's a very good start for a song, but what about the second line?

20:42.000 --> 20:48.000
He tried singing ho two or three times, but it didn't seem to help.

20:48.000 --> 20:56.000
Perhaps it would be better, he thought, if I sang hi for the life of a bear,

20:56.000 --> 21:00.000
so he sang it, but it wasn't.

21:00.000 --> 21:06.000
Very well then, he said, I shall sing that first line twice.

21:06.000 --> 21:11.000
And perhaps if I sing it very quickly, I shall find myself singing the third and fourth lines

21:11.000 --> 21:16.000
before I have time to think of them, and that will be a good song.

21:16.000 --> 21:21.000
Now then, sing ho for the life of a bear.

21:21.000 --> 21:25.000
Sing ho for the life of a bear.

21:25.000 --> 21:28.000
I don't much mind if it rains or snows,

21:28.000 --> 21:31.000
because I've got a lot of honey on my nice new nose.

21:31.000 --> 21:34.000
I don't much care if it snows or thaws,

21:34.000 --> 21:37.000
because I've got a lot of honey on my nice clean paws.

21:37.000 --> 21:40.000
Sing ho for a bear.

21:40.000 --> 21:48.000
Sing ho for a poo and I'll have a little something in an hour or two.

21:48.000 --> 21:54.000
He was so pleased with this song that he sang it all the way to the top of the forest.

21:54.000 --> 21:57.000
And if I go on singing much longer, he thought,

21:57.000 --> 22:03.000
it will be time for the little something, and then the last line won't be true.

22:03.000 --> 22:07.000
So he turned it into a hum instead.

22:07.000 --> 22:12.000
Christopher Robin was sitting outside his door, putting on his big boots.

22:12.000 --> 22:18.000
As soon as he saw the big boots, poo knew that an adventure was going to happen.

22:18.000 --> 22:21.000
And he brushed the honey off his nose with the back of his paw

22:21.000 --> 22:27.000
and spruced himself up as well as he could, so as to look ready for anything.

22:27.000 --> 22:30.000
Good morning, Christopher Robin, he called out.

22:30.000 --> 22:34.000
Hello, poo bear, I can't get this boot on.

22:34.000 --> 22:37.000
That's bad, said poo.

22:37.000 --> 22:40.000
Do you think you could very kindly lean against me,

22:40.000 --> 22:44.000
because I keep pulling so hard that I fall over backwards?

22:44.000 --> 22:48.000
Poo sat down, dug his feet into the ground,

22:48.000 --> 22:51.000
and pushed hard against Christopher Robin's back.

22:51.000 --> 22:54.000
And Christopher Robin pushed hard against his,

22:54.000 --> 22:58.000
and pulled and pulled his boot until he had got it on.

22:58.000 --> 23:01.000
And that's that, said poo.

23:01.000 --> 23:03.000
What do we do next?

23:03.000 --> 23:08.000
We are all going on an expedition, said Christopher Robin, as he got up and brushed himself.

23:08.000 --> 23:10.000
Thank you, poo.

23:10.000 --> 23:14.000
Going on an expedition, said poo eagerly,

23:14.000 --> 23:16.000
I don't think I've ever been on one of those.

23:16.000 --> 23:19.000
Where are we going to on this expedition?

23:19.000 --> 23:22.000
Expedition, silly old bear.

23:22.000 --> 23:24.000
It's got an X in it.

23:24.000 --> 23:26.000
Oh, said poo.

23:26.000 --> 23:29.000
I know, but he didn't really.

23:29.000 --> 23:33.000
We're going to discover the North Pole.

23:33.000 --> 23:36.000
Oh, said poo again.

23:36.000 --> 23:39.000
What is the North Pole, he asked?

23:39.000 --> 23:43.000
Just a thing you discover, said Christopher Robin carelessly,

23:43.000 --> 23:45.000
not being quite sure himself.

23:45.000 --> 23:48.000
Oh, I see, said poo.

23:48.000 --> 23:52.000
Are bears any good at discovering it?

23:52.000 --> 23:54.000
Of course they are.

23:54.000 --> 23:58.000
And rabbit, and kanga, and all of you, it's an expedition.

23:58.000 --> 24:03.000
That's what an expedition means, a long line of everybody.

24:03.000 --> 24:07.000
You better tell the others to get ready while I see my guns all right.

24:07.000 --> 24:10.000
And we must all bring provisions.

24:10.000 --> 24:12.000
Bring what?

24:12.000 --> 24:13.000
Things to eat.

24:13.000 --> 24:16.000
Oh, said poo happily.

24:16.000 --> 24:19.000
I thought you said provisions.

24:19.000 --> 24:21.000
I'll go and tell them.

24:21.000 --> 24:23.000
And he stumped off.

24:23.000 --> 24:26.000
The first person he met was rabbit.

24:26.000 --> 24:29.000
Hello, rabbit, he said, is that you?

24:29.000 --> 24:33.000
Let's pretend it isn't, said rabbit, and see what happens.

24:33.000 --> 24:35.000
I've got a message for you.

24:35.000 --> 24:36.000
I'll give it to him.

24:36.000 --> 24:41.000
We're all going on an expedition with Christopher Robin.

24:41.000 --> 24:43.000
What is it when we're on it?

24:43.000 --> 24:46.000
A sort of boat, I think, said poo.

24:46.000 --> 24:48.000
Oh, that's sort.

24:48.000 --> 24:52.000
Yes, and we're going to discover a pole or something.

24:52.000 --> 24:54.000
Or was it a mole?

24:54.000 --> 24:57.000
Anyhow, we're going to discover it.

24:57.000 --> 24:58.000
We are, are we?

24:58.000 --> 24:59.000
Said rabbit.

24:59.000 --> 25:04.000
Yes, and we've got to bring pro things to eat with us

25:04.000 --> 25:06.000
in case we want to eat them.

25:06.000 --> 25:08.000
Now I'm going down to piglets.

25:08.000 --> 25:10.000
Tell kanga, will you?

25:10.000 --> 25:14.000
He left rabbit and hurried down to piglets' house.

25:14.000 --> 25:17.000
The piglet was sitting on the ground at the door of his house,

25:17.000 --> 25:19.000
blowing happily at a dandelion,

25:19.000 --> 25:25.000
and wondering whether it would be this year, next year, sometime or never.

25:25.000 --> 25:28.000
He had just discovered that it would be never.

25:28.000 --> 25:31.000
I was trying to remember what it was

25:31.000 --> 25:33.000
and hoping it wasn't anything nice.

25:33.000 --> 25:35.000
When poo came up.

25:35.000 --> 25:38.000
Oh, piglet, said poo excitedly.

25:38.000 --> 25:41.000
We're going on an expedition, all of us with things to eat,

25:41.000 --> 25:43.000
to discover something.

25:43.000 --> 25:45.000
To discover what?

25:45.000 --> 25:47.000
Said piglet, anxiously.

25:47.000 --> 25:50.000
Oh, just something.

25:50.000 --> 25:53.000
Nothing fierce.

25:53.000 --> 25:56.000
Christopher Robin didn't say anything about fierce.

25:56.000 --> 25:59.000
He just said it had an X.

25:59.000 --> 26:02.000
It isn't their next, her mind.

26:02.000 --> 26:04.000
Said piglet, earnestly.

26:04.000 --> 26:07.000
It said teeth, but if Christopher Robin is coming,

26:07.000 --> 26:10.000
I don't mind anything.

26:10.000 --> 26:13.000
In a little while they were all ready at the top of the forest,

26:13.000 --> 26:16.000
and the expedition started.

26:16.000 --> 26:19.000
First came Christopher Robin and rabbit,

26:19.000 --> 26:21.000
then piglet and poo,

26:21.000 --> 26:24.000
then kanga, with ruin her pocket,

26:24.000 --> 26:27.000
and owl, then eaw,

26:27.000 --> 26:30.000
and at the end, in a long line,

26:30.000 --> 26:34.000
all rabbits, friends, and relations.

26:34.000 --> 26:37.000
I didn't ask them, explain rabbit carelessly.

26:37.000 --> 26:38.000
They just came.

26:38.000 --> 26:39.000
They always do.

26:39.000 --> 26:42.000
They can march at the end after eaw.

26:42.000 --> 26:46.000
What I say, said eaw,

26:46.000 --> 26:49.000
is that it's unsettling.

26:49.000 --> 26:53.000
I didn't want to come on this expo,

26:53.000 --> 26:55.000
what poo said.

26:55.000 --> 26:59.000
I only came to oblige, but here I am,

26:59.000 --> 27:03.000
and if I am the end of the expo,

27:03.000 --> 27:05.000
what we're talking about,

27:05.000 --> 27:08.000
then let me be the end.

27:08.000 --> 27:12.000
But if every time I want to sit down for a little rest,

27:12.000 --> 27:16.000
I have to brush away half a dozen of rabbits,

27:16.000 --> 27:19.000
smaller friends and relations first,

27:19.000 --> 27:24.000
then this isn't an expo, whatever it is at all.

27:24.000 --> 27:27.000
It's simply a confused noise.

27:27.000 --> 27:30.000
That's what I say.

27:30.000 --> 27:33.000
I see what eaw means, said owl.

27:33.000 --> 27:35.000
If you ask me,

27:35.000 --> 27:39.000
I'm not asking anybody, said eaw.

27:39.000 --> 27:43.000
I'm just telling everybody.

27:43.000 --> 27:45.000
We can look for the North Pole,

27:45.000 --> 27:47.000
or we can play,

27:47.000 --> 27:49.000
here we go gathering nuts and may,

27:49.000 --> 27:52.000
with the end part of an ant's nest.

27:52.000 --> 27:55.000
It's all the same to me.

27:55.000 --> 27:58.000
There was a shout from the top of the line.

27:58.000 --> 27:59.000
Come on,

27:59.000 --> 28:01.000
called Christopher Robin.

28:01.000 --> 28:03.000
Come on, called poo and piglet.

28:03.000 --> 28:05.000
Come on, called owl.

28:05.000 --> 28:07.000
We're starting, said rabbit.

28:07.000 --> 28:08.000
I must go,

28:08.000 --> 28:10.000
and he hurried after the front of the expedition

28:10.000 --> 28:12.000
with Christopher Robin.

28:12.000 --> 28:15.000
All right, said eaw.

28:15.000 --> 28:17.000
We're going,

28:17.000 --> 28:21.000
only don't blame me.

28:22.000 --> 28:25.000
So off they all went to discover the pole.

28:25.000 --> 28:27.000
And as they walked,

28:27.000 --> 28:29.000
they chatted to each other of this and that,

28:29.000 --> 28:33.000
all except poo, who was making up a song.

28:33.000 --> 28:36.000
This is the first verse he said to piglet

28:36.000 --> 28:38.000
when he was ready with it.

28:38.000 --> 28:40.000
First verse of what?

28:40.000 --> 28:41.000
My song.

28:41.000 --> 28:43.000
What song?

28:43.000 --> 28:44.000
This one,

28:44.000 --> 28:45.000
which one?

28:45.000 --> 28:47.000
Well, if you listen, piglet,

28:47.000 --> 28:48.000
you'll hear it.

28:48.000 --> 28:51.000
How do you know I'm not listening?

28:51.000 --> 28:54.000
Poo couldn't answer that one.

28:54.000 --> 28:56.000
So he began to sing.

28:56.000 --> 28:59.000
They all went off to discover the pole,

28:59.000 --> 29:02.000
owl and piglet and rabbit and all.

29:02.000 --> 29:05.000
It's a thing you discover as I've been told

29:05.000 --> 29:08.000
by owl and piglet and rabbit and all.

29:08.000 --> 29:12.000
Eaw Christopher Robin and poo and rabbit's relations

29:12.000 --> 29:15.000
all went to.

29:15.000 --> 29:20.000
And where the pole was none of them knew.

29:20.000 --> 29:24.000
Sing hey for owl and rabbit and all.

29:24.000 --> 29:25.000
Hush.

29:25.000 --> 29:26.000
Said Christopher Robin,

29:26.000 --> 29:28.000
turning round to poo.

29:28.000 --> 29:31.000
We're just coming to a dangerous place.

29:31.000 --> 29:32.000
Hush.

29:32.000 --> 29:33.000
Said poo.

29:33.000 --> 29:35.000
Turning round quickly to piglet.

29:35.000 --> 29:36.000
Hush.

29:36.000 --> 29:38.000
Said piglet to kanga.

29:38.000 --> 29:39.000
Hush.

29:39.000 --> 29:40.000
Said kanga to owl,

29:40.000 --> 29:44.000
while Rue said Hush several times to himself,

29:44.000 --> 29:45.000
but he quieted.

29:45.000 --> 29:46.000
Hush.

29:46.000 --> 29:48.000
Said owl to Eaw.

29:48.000 --> 29:50.000
Hush.

29:50.000 --> 29:54.000
Said Eaw in a terrible voice to all rabbit's friends

29:54.000 --> 29:57.000
and relations and Hush they said hastily to each other,

29:57.000 --> 30:02.000
all down the line until it got to the last one of all.

30:02.000 --> 30:06.000
And the last and smallest friend and relation was so upset

30:06.000 --> 30:10.000
to find that the whole expedition was saying Hush to him

30:10.000 --> 30:13.000
that he buried himself head downwards in a crack in the ground

30:13.000 --> 30:17.000
and stayed there for two days until the danger was over

30:17.000 --> 30:19.000
and then went home in a great hurry

30:19.000 --> 30:22.000
and lived quietly with his aunt ever afterwards.

30:22.000 --> 30:27.000
His name was Alexander Beatle.

30:27.000 --> 30:30.000
They had come to a stream which twisted and tumbled

30:30.000 --> 30:32.000
between high rocky banks

30:32.000 --> 30:36.000
and Christopher Robin saw at once how dangerous it was.

30:36.000 --> 30:41.000
It's just the place he explained for an ambush.

30:41.000 --> 30:44.000
What sort of bush whispered poo to piglet?

30:44.000 --> 30:46.000
A gorse bush?

30:46.000 --> 30:49.000
My dear poo, said owl in his superior way,

30:49.000 --> 30:52.000
don't you know what an ambush is?

30:52.000 --> 30:53.000
Owl?

30:53.000 --> 30:56.000
Said piglet, looking round at him severely.

30:56.000 --> 31:00.000
Poof whisper was a perfectly private whisper

31:00.000 --> 31:02.000
and there was no need.

31:02.000 --> 31:07.000
An ambush, said owl, is a sort of surprise.

31:07.000 --> 31:11.000
So is a gorse bush sometimes, said poo.

31:11.000 --> 31:15.000
An ambush, as I was about to explain to poo, said piglet,

31:15.000 --> 31:18.000
is a sort of surprise.

31:18.000 --> 31:23.000
If people jump out at you suddenly, that's an ambush, said owl.

31:23.000 --> 31:30.000
It's an ambush poo when people jump at you suddenly, explained piglet.

31:30.000 --> 31:34.000
Poo, who now knew what an ambush was, said that a gorse bush

31:34.000 --> 31:37.000
had sprung at him suddenly one day when he fell off a tree

31:37.000 --> 31:41.000
and he had taken six days to get all the prickles out of himself.

31:41.000 --> 31:47.000
We are not talking about gorse bushes, said owl, a little crossly.

31:47.000 --> 31:50.000
I am, said poo.

31:50.000 --> 31:53.000
They were climbing very cautiously up the stream now,

31:53.000 --> 31:55.000
going from rock to rock.

31:55.000 --> 31:57.000
And after they'd gone a little way, they came to a place

31:57.000 --> 32:00.000
where the banks widened out at each side,

32:00.000 --> 32:02.000
so that on each side of the water,

32:02.000 --> 32:07.000
there was a level strip of grass on which they could sit down and rest.

32:07.000 --> 32:10.000
As soon as he saw this, Christopher Robin called,

32:10.000 --> 32:15.000
halt, and they all sat down and rested.

32:15.000 --> 32:20.000
I think, said Christopher Robin, that we ought to eat all our provisions now,

32:20.000 --> 32:23.000
so that we shan't have so much to carry.

32:23.000 --> 32:26.000
Eat all our what, said poo.

32:26.000 --> 32:29.000
All that we've brought, said piglet, getting to work.

32:29.000 --> 32:32.000
That's a good idea, said poo.

32:32.000 --> 32:34.000
And he got to work too.

32:34.000 --> 32:36.000
Have you all got something?

32:36.000 --> 32:38.000
Ask Christopher Robin with his mouth full.

32:38.000 --> 32:41.000
All except me.

32:41.000 --> 32:42.000
Said Eor.

32:42.000 --> 32:45.000
As usual.

32:45.000 --> 32:49.000
He looked round at them in his melancholy way.

32:49.000 --> 32:55.000
I suppose none of you were sitting on a thistle by an enchant.

32:55.000 --> 32:58.000
I believe I am, said poo.

32:58.000 --> 32:59.000
Ow!

32:59.000 --> 33:01.000
He got up and looked behind him.

33:01.000 --> 33:03.000
Yes, I was.

33:03.000 --> 33:05.000
I thought so.

33:05.000 --> 33:07.000
Thank you, poo.

33:07.000 --> 33:11.000
If you've quite finished with it.

33:11.000 --> 33:15.000
He moved across to poo's place and began to eat.

33:15.000 --> 33:18.000
It doesn't do them any good, you know.

33:18.000 --> 33:22.000
Sitting on them, he went on, as he looked up, munching.

33:22.000 --> 33:25.000
Takes all the life out of them.

33:25.000 --> 33:28.000
Remember that another time.

33:28.000 --> 33:30.000
All of you.

33:30.000 --> 33:32.000
A little consideration.

33:32.000 --> 33:37.000
A little thought for others makes all the difference.

33:37.000 --> 33:41.000
As soon as he had finished his lunch, Christopher Robin whispered to Rabbit,

33:41.000 --> 33:44.000
and Rabbit said, yes, yes, of course.

33:44.000 --> 33:47.000
And they walked a little way up the stream together.

33:47.000 --> 33:50.000
I didn't want the others to hear, said Christopher Robin.

33:50.000 --> 33:52.000
Quite so, said Rabbit.

33:52.000 --> 33:53.000
Looking important.

33:53.000 --> 33:57.000
It's, I wonder it, it's only...

33:57.000 --> 34:00.000
Rabbit, I suppose you don't know.

34:00.000 --> 34:04.000
What does the North Pole look like?

34:04.000 --> 34:07.000
Well, said Rabbit, stroking his whiskers.

34:07.000 --> 34:10.000
Now you're asking me.

34:10.000 --> 34:14.000
I did know once only I've sort of forgotten, said Christopher Robin, carelessly.

34:14.000 --> 34:18.000
It's a funny thing, said Rabbit, but I've sort of forgotten too.

34:18.000 --> 34:23.000
Although I did know once, I suppose it's just a pole stuck in the ground.

34:23.000 --> 34:27.000
Sure to be a pole, said Rabbit, because of calling it a pole.

34:27.000 --> 34:31.000
And if it's a pole, well, I should think it would be sticking in the ground, shouldn't you?

34:31.000 --> 34:34.000
Because there'd be nowhere else to stick it.

34:34.000 --> 34:36.000
Yes, that's what I thought.

34:36.000 --> 34:41.000
The only thing, said Rabbit, is where is it sticking?

34:41.000 --> 34:45.000
That's what we're looking for, said Christopher Robin.

34:45.000 --> 34:47.000
They went back to the others.

34:47.000 --> 34:50.000
Piglet was lying on his back, sleeping peacefully.

34:50.000 --> 34:53.000
Rue was washing his face and paws in the stream,

34:53.000 --> 35:00.000
while Canger explained to everybody proudly that this was the first time he had ever washed his face himself.

35:00.000 --> 35:06.000
And all was telling Canger an interesting anecdote full of long words like encyclopedia

35:06.000 --> 35:10.000
and rhododendron to which Canger wasn't listening.

35:10.000 --> 35:14.000
I don't all with all his washing grumbled ear.

35:14.000 --> 35:18.000
This modern behind the ears nonsense.

35:18.000 --> 35:21.000
What do you think, Pooh?

35:21.000 --> 35:29.000
Well, said Pooh, I think, but we shall never know what Pooh thought.

35:29.000 --> 35:36.000
For they came a sudden squeak from Rue, a splash, and a loud cry of alarm from Canger.

35:36.000 --> 35:40.000
So much for washing, said Eor.

35:40.000 --> 35:46.000
Rue's fallen in, cried Rabbit, and he and Christopher Robin came rushing down to the rescue.

35:46.000 --> 35:49.000
Look at me, swimming!

35:49.000 --> 35:54.000
Sweet Rue, from the middle of his pool, and was hurried down a waterfall into the next pool.

35:54.000 --> 35:56.000
Are you all right, Rue, dear?

35:56.000 --> 35:58.000
called Canger, anxiously.

35:58.000 --> 36:00.000
Yes, said Rue.

36:00.000 --> 36:02.000
Look at me, sweet!

36:02.000 --> 36:06.000
And down he went over the next waterfall into another pool.

36:06.000 --> 36:09.000
Everybody was doing something to help.

36:09.000 --> 36:13.000
Piglet wide awake suddenly was jumping up and down and making,

36:13.000 --> 36:15.000
Oh, I say, noises.

36:15.000 --> 36:19.000
Owl was explaining that in a case of sudden and temporary immersion,

36:19.000 --> 36:22.000
the important thing was to keep the head above water.

36:22.000 --> 36:25.000
Canger was jumping along the bank saying,

36:25.000 --> 36:27.000
Are you sure you're all right, Rue, dear?

36:27.000 --> 36:30.000
To which Rue, from whatever pool he was in at the moment, was answering,

36:30.000 --> 36:33.000
Little Beast, swimming!

36:33.000 --> 36:38.000
Eor had turned round and hung his tail over the first pool into which Rue fell,

36:38.000 --> 36:42.000
and with his back to the accident was grumbling quietly to himself and saying,

36:42.000 --> 36:49.000
Oh, this washing, but catch on to my tail, little Rue, and you'll be all right.

36:49.000 --> 36:55.000
And Christopher Robin and Rabbit came hurrying past Eor and were calling out to the others in front of them.

36:55.000 --> 36:57.000
All right, Rue, I'm coming!

36:57.000 --> 37:02.000
Oh, Christopher Robin, get something across the stream lower down, some of you fellas, called Rabbit.

37:02.000 --> 37:06.000
But Poo was getting something.

37:06.000 --> 37:11.000
Two pools below Rue, he was standing with a long pole in his paws,

37:11.000 --> 37:17.000
and Canger came up and took one end of it, and between them they held it across the lower part of the pool.

37:17.000 --> 37:20.000
And Rue still bubbling proudly.

37:20.000 --> 37:22.000
Look at me, swimming!

37:22.000 --> 37:25.000
Drifted up against it and climbed out.

37:25.000 --> 37:27.000
Did you see me swimming?

37:27.000 --> 37:30.000
Squeaked Rue excitedly, while Canger scolded him and rubbed him down.

37:30.000 --> 37:36.000
Poo, did you see me swimming? That's called swimming! What I was doing? Rabbit, did you see what I was doing?

37:36.000 --> 37:41.000
Swimming, and I picked it! I said I picked it! What do you think I was doing? Swimming!

37:41.000 --> 37:44.000
Christopher Robin, did you see me?

37:44.000 --> 37:49.000
But Christopher Robin wasn't listening. He was looking at Poo.

37:49.000 --> 37:54.000
Poo, he said, where did you find that pole?

37:54.000 --> 37:57.000
Poo looked at the pole in his hands.

37:57.000 --> 38:03.000
I just found it, he said. I thought it ought to be useful, I just picked it up.

38:03.000 --> 38:07.000
Poo, said Christopher Robin solemnly.

38:07.000 --> 38:14.000
The expedition is over. You have found the North Pole.

38:14.000 --> 38:19.000
Oh, said Poo.

38:19.000 --> 38:23.000
Eor was sitting with his tail in the water when they all got back to him.

38:23.000 --> 38:27.000
Tell Rue to be quick, somebody, he said.

38:27.000 --> 38:34.000
My tail's getting cold. I don't want to mention it, but I just mention it.

38:34.000 --> 38:39.000
I don't want to complain, but there it is. My tail's cold.

38:39.000 --> 38:42.000
Here I am, Squeaked Rue.

38:42.000 --> 38:45.000
Oh, there you are.

38:45.000 --> 38:48.000
Did you see me swimming?

38:48.000 --> 38:53.000
Eor took his tail out of the water and swished it from side to side.

38:53.000 --> 38:59.000
As I expected, he said, lost all feeling.

38:59.000 --> 39:04.000
Numbed it. That's what it's done. Numbed it.

39:04.000 --> 39:09.000
Well, as long as nobody minds, I suppose it's all right.

39:09.000 --> 39:13.000
Poor old Eor. I'll dry it for you, said Christopher Robin.

39:13.000 --> 39:16.000
And he took out his handkerchief and rubbed it up.

39:16.000 --> 39:23.000
Thank you, Christopher Robin. You're the only one who seems to understand about tails.

39:23.000 --> 39:28.000
They don't think that's what's the matter with some of these others.

39:28.000 --> 39:34.000
They've no imagination. A tail isn't a tail to them.

39:34.000 --> 39:38.000
It's just a little bit extra at the back.

39:38.000 --> 39:42.000
Never mind, Eor, said Christopher Robin, rubbing his hardest.

39:42.000 --> 39:44.000
Is that better?

39:44.000 --> 39:48.000
It's feeling more like a tail, perhaps.

39:48.000 --> 39:52.000
It belongs again, if you know what I mean.

39:52.000 --> 39:56.000
Hello, Eor, said Pooh, coming up to them with his pole.

39:56.000 --> 40:04.000
Hello, Pooh. Thank you for asking, but I shall be able to use it again in a day or two.

40:04.000 --> 40:07.000
Use what, said Pooh.

40:07.000 --> 40:10.000
What we're talking about.

40:10.000 --> 40:14.000
I wasn't talking about anything, said Pooh, looking puzzled.

40:14.000 --> 40:21.000
My mistake again, I thought you were saying how sorry you were about my tail being all numb.

40:21.000 --> 40:24.000
And could you do anything to help?

40:24.000 --> 40:28.000
No, said Pooh. That wasn't me, he said.

40:28.000 --> 40:32.000
He thought for a little, and then suggested, hopefully.

40:32.000 --> 40:35.000
Perhaps it was somebody else.

40:35.000 --> 40:40.000
Well, thank him for me when you see him.

40:40.000 --> 40:44.000
Pooh looked anxiously at Christopher Robin.

40:44.000 --> 40:48.000
Pooh's found the North Pole, said Christopher Robin. Isn't that lovely?

40:48.000 --> 40:51.000
Pooh looked modestly down.

40:51.000 --> 40:53.000
Is that it?

40:53.000 --> 40:56.000
Said Eor. Yes, said Christopher Robin.

40:56.000 --> 40:59.000
Is that what we were looking for?

40:59.000 --> 41:02.000
Yes, said Pooh.

41:02.000 --> 41:06.000
Oh, said Eor.

41:06.000 --> 41:12.000
Well, anyhow, it didn't rain, he said.

41:12.000 --> 41:16.000
They stuck the pole in the ground, and Christopher Robin tied a message onto it.

41:16.000 --> 41:24.000
North Pole, discovered by Pooh. Pooh found it.

41:24.000 --> 41:26.000
Then they all went home again.

41:26.000 --> 41:33.000
And I think, but I'm not quite sure, that Rue had a hot bath and went straight to bed.

41:33.000 --> 41:38.000
But Pooh went back to his own house, and feeling very proud of what he had done,

41:38.000 --> 41:43.000
had a little something to revive himself.

41:43.000 --> 41:56.000
Chapter 9, in which Piglet is entirely surrounded by water.

41:56.000 --> 42:02.000
It rained, and it rained, and it rained.

42:02.000 --> 42:09.000
Piglet told himself that never, in all his life, and he was goodness knows how old,

42:09.000 --> 42:18.000
three was it, or four, never had he seen so much rain, days and days and days.

42:18.000 --> 42:24.000
If only, he thought, as he looked out of the window, I had been in Pooh's household,

42:24.000 --> 42:27.000
Christopher Robin's household, rabbit's house when it began to rain,

42:27.000 --> 42:30.000
then I should have had company all this time instead of being here,

42:30.000 --> 42:34.000
all alone with nothing to do except wonder when it will stop.

42:34.000 --> 42:36.000
And he imagined himself with Pooh saying,

42:36.000 --> 42:39.000
Did you ever see such rain, Pooh?

42:39.000 --> 42:42.000
And Pooh saying, isn't it awful, Piglet, and Piglet saying,

42:42.000 --> 42:45.000
I wonder how it is, have a Christopher Robin's way?

42:45.000 --> 42:50.000
And Pooh saying, I should think poor old rabbit is about flooded out by this time.

42:50.000 --> 42:56.000
It would have been jolly to talk like this, and really, it wasn't much good having anything exciting like floods

42:56.000 --> 43:01.000
if you couldn't share them with somebody, for it was rather exciting.

43:01.000 --> 43:06.000
The little dry ditches in which Piglet had knows about so often had become streams.

43:06.000 --> 43:10.000
The little streams across which he had splashed were rivers,

43:10.000 --> 43:16.000
and the river between whose steep banks they had played so happily had sprawled out of its own bed

43:16.000 --> 43:24.000
and was taking up so much room everywhere that Piglet was beginning to wonder whether it would be coming into his bed soon.

43:24.000 --> 43:32.000
It's a little anxious, he said to himself, to be a very small animal entirely surrounded by water.

43:32.000 --> 43:40.000
Christopher Robin and Pooh could escape by climbing trees and kanga could escape by jumping and rabbit could escape by burrowing

43:40.000 --> 43:46.000
and how could escape by flying and you or could escape by making a loud noise until rescued

43:46.000 --> 43:52.000
and here am I surrounded by water and I can't do anything.

43:52.000 --> 43:59.000
It went on raining and every day the water got a little higher until now it was nearly up to Piglet's window

43:59.000 --> 44:02.000
and still he hadn't done anything.

44:02.000 --> 44:09.000
There's Pooh, he thought to himself. Pooh hasn't much brain, but he never comes to any harm.

44:09.000 --> 44:13.000
He does silly things and they turn out right.

44:13.000 --> 44:19.000
That's Howell. Howell hasn't exactly got brain, but he knows things.

44:19.000 --> 44:23.000
He would know the right thing to do when surrounded by water.

44:23.000 --> 44:29.000
There's rabbit, he hasn't learnt in books, but he can always think of a clever plan.

44:29.000 --> 44:39.000
There's kanga, she isn't clever, kanga isn't, but she would be so anxious about Rue that she would do a good thing to do without thinking about it.

44:39.000 --> 44:49.000
And then there's eel, and eel is so miserable anyhow that he wouldn't mind about this, but I wonder what Christopher Robin would do.

44:49.000 --> 44:56.000
Then suddenly he remembered a story which Christopher Robin had told him about a man on a desert island

44:56.000 --> 45:01.000
who had written something in a bottle and thrown it into the sea.

45:01.000 --> 45:09.000
And Piglet thought that if he wrote something in a bottle and threw it in the water, perhaps somebody would come and rescue him.

45:09.000 --> 45:19.000
He left the window and began to search his house, all of it that wasn't under water, and at last he found a pencil and a small piece of dry paper and a bottle with a cork to it.

45:19.000 --> 45:29.000
And he wrote on one side of the paper, Help! Piglet! Me! And on the other side, it's me, Piglet! Help! Help!

45:29.000 --> 45:43.000
Then he put the paper in the bottle and he corked the bottle up as tightly as he could, and he lent out of his window as far as he could lean without falling in, and he threw the bottle as far as he could throw. Splash!

45:43.000 --> 45:53.000
And in a little while it bobbed up again on the water, and he watched it floating slowly away in the distance until his eyes ached with looking.

45:53.000 --> 46:00.000
And sometimes he thought it was the bottle, and sometimes he thought it was just a ripple on the water which he was following.

46:00.000 --> 46:10.000
And then suddenly he knew that he would never see it again, and that he had done all that he could do to save himself.

46:10.000 --> 46:24.000
So now he thought somebody else will have to do something, and I hope they'll do it soon because if they don't, I shall have to swim, which I can't, so I hope they'll do it soon.

46:24.000 --> 46:36.000
And then he gave a very long sigh and said, I wish Pooh were here, he's so much more friendly with too.

46:36.000 --> 46:49.000
When the rain began, Pooh was asleep. It rained, and it rained, and it rained, and he slept, and he slept, and he slept.

46:49.000 --> 47:04.000
He had had a tiring day. You remember how he discovered the North Pole? Well, he was so proud of this that he asked Christopher Robin if there were any other poles such as a bear of little brain might discover.

47:04.000 --> 47:13.000
There's a South Pole, said Christopher Robin, and I expect there's an East Pole and a West Pole, though people don't like talking about them.

47:13.000 --> 47:20.000
Pooh was very excited when he heard this, and suggested that they should have an expedition to discover the East Pole.

47:20.000 --> 47:28.000
But Christopher Robin had thought of something else to do with Kanga, so Pooh went out to discover the East Pole by himself.

47:29.000 --> 47:45.000
Whether he discovered it or not, I forget, but he was so tired when he got home that in the very middle of his supper, after he'd been eating for little more than half an hour, he fell fast asleep in his chair, and slept, and slept, and slept.

47:46.000 --> 47:57.000
Then, suddenly, he was dreaming. He was at the East Pole, and it was a very cold pole, with the coldest sort of snow and ice all over it.

47:57.000 --> 48:06.000
He had found a beehive to sleep in, but there wasn't room for his legs, so he'd left them outside.

48:07.000 --> 48:14.000
And wild woozels, such as inhabit the East Pole, came and nibbled all the fur off his legs to make nests for their young.

48:14.000 --> 48:21.000
And the more they nibbled, the colder his legs got, until suddenly he woke up with them, aah!

48:21.000 --> 48:29.000
And there he was, sitting in his chair, with his feet in the water, and water all round him.

48:30.000 --> 48:33.000
He splashed to his door and looked out.

48:33.000 --> 48:38.000
This is serious, said Pooh. I must have an escape!

48:38.000 --> 48:48.000
So he took his largest pot of honey and escaped with it, to a broad branch of history, well above the water, and then he climbed down again and escaped with another pot.

48:48.000 --> 48:57.000
And when the whole escape was finished, there was Pooh sitting on his branch, dangling his legs, and there beside him were ten pots of honey.

48:57.000 --> 49:06.000
Two days later, there was Pooh sitting on his branch, dangling his legs, and there beside him were four pots of honey.

49:06.000 --> 49:15.000
Three days later, there was Pooh sitting on his branch, dangling his legs, and there beside him was one pot of honey.

49:15.000 --> 49:19.000
Four days later, there was Pooh.

49:19.000 --> 49:29.000
And it was on the morning of the fourth day, that piglet's bottle came floating past him, and with one loud cry of honey!

49:29.000 --> 49:35.000
Pooh plunged into the water, seized the bottle, and struggled back to history again.

49:35.000 --> 49:40.000
Bother, said Pooh, as he opened it, all that wet for nothing.

49:40.000 --> 49:43.000
What's that bit of paper doing?

49:43.000 --> 49:46.000
He took it out and looked.

49:46.000 --> 49:50.000
It's a message, he said to himself. That's what it is.

49:50.000 --> 50:02.000
And that letter is a P, and so is that, and so is that, and P means Pooh, so it's a very important message to me.

50:02.000 --> 50:14.000
And I can't read it. I must find Christopher Robin, or Owl, or Piglet, one of those clever readers who can read things, and they will tell me what this message means.

50:14.000 --> 50:18.000
Only I can't swim. Bother.

50:18.000 --> 50:25.000
Then he had an idea, and I think that for a bear of very little brain, it was a good idea.

50:25.000 --> 50:38.000
He said to himself, if a bottle can float, then a jar can float, and if a jar floats, I can sit on the top of it, if it's a very big jar.

50:38.000 --> 50:43.000
So he took his biggest jar and caught it up.

50:43.000 --> 50:51.000
All boats have to have a name, he said. So I shall call mine the floating bear.

50:51.000 --> 50:56.000
And with these words, he dropped his boat into the water and jumped in after it.

50:56.000 --> 51:04.000
For a little while, Pooh and the floating bear were uncertain as to which of them was meant to be on the top.

51:04.000 --> 51:16.000
But after trying one or two different positions, they settled down with the floating bear underneath, and Pooh, triumphantly, has strided, paddling vigorously with his feet.

51:16.000 --> 51:20.000
Christopher Robin lived at the very top of the forest.

51:20.000 --> 51:28.000
It rained, and it rained, and it rained. But the water couldn't come up to his house.

51:28.000 --> 51:32.000
It was rather jolly to look down into the valleys and see the water all around him.

51:32.000 --> 51:38.000
But it rained so hard that he stayed indoors most of the time and thought about things.

51:38.000 --> 51:43.000
Every morning he went out with his umbrella and put a stick in the place where the water came up to.

51:43.000 --> 51:47.000
And every next morning he went out and couldn't see his stick anymore.

51:47.000 --> 51:51.000
So he put another stick in the place where the water came up to.

51:51.000 --> 52:00.000
And then he walked home again, and each morning he had a shorter way to walk than he had had the morning before.

52:00.000 --> 52:06.000
On the morning of the fifth day, he saw the water all around him

52:06.000 --> 52:14.000
and knew that for the first time in his life he was on a real island, which was very exciting.

52:14.000 --> 52:21.000
It was on this morning that Owl came flying over the water to say, how do you do to his friend Christopher Robin?

52:21.000 --> 52:26.000
I say, Owl, isn't this fun? I'm on an island.

52:26.000 --> 52:32.000
The atmospheric conditions have been very unfavorable lately, said Owl.

52:32.000 --> 52:37.000
The what? It has been raining, explained Owl.

52:37.000 --> 52:40.000
Yes, said Christopher Robin. It has.

52:40.000 --> 52:45.000
The flood level has reached an unprecedented height.

52:45.000 --> 52:49.000
The who? There's a lot of water about, explained Owl.

52:49.000 --> 52:52.000
Yes, said Christopher Robin. There is.

52:52.000 --> 52:56.000
However, the prospects are rapidly becoming more favorable.

52:56.000 --> 53:00.000
At any moment, have you seen Pooh?

53:00.000 --> 53:05.000
No. At any moment, I hope he's all right, said Christopher Robin.

53:05.000 --> 53:08.000
I've been wondering about him. I expect piglets with him.

53:08.000 --> 53:10.000
Do you think they're all right, Owl?

53:10.000 --> 53:18.000
I expect so. You'll see. At any moment, do go and see Owl, because Pooh hasn't got very much brain and he might do something silly.

53:18.000 --> 53:22.000
And I do love him, so Owl. Do you see Owl?

53:22.000 --> 53:27.000
That's all right, said Owl. I'll go back directly.

53:27.000 --> 53:32.000
And he flew off. In a little while, he was back again.

53:32.000 --> 53:37.000
Pooh isn't there, he said. Not there.

53:37.000 --> 53:44.000
He's been there. He's been sitting on a branch of his tree outside his house with nine pots of honey.

53:44.000 --> 53:47.000
But he isn't there now.

53:47.000 --> 53:51.000
Oh, Pooh, cried Christopher Robin. Where are you?

53:51.000 --> 53:56.000
Here I am, said a growly voice behind him.

53:56.000 --> 54:01.000
Pooh! They rushed into each other's arms.

54:01.000 --> 54:07.000
How did you get here, Pooh? asked Christopher Robin when he was ready to talk again.

54:07.000 --> 54:11.000
On my boat, said Pooh proudly.

54:11.000 --> 54:15.000
I had a very important message sent me in a bottle.

54:15.000 --> 54:23.000
And owing to having got some water in my eyes, I couldn't read it, so I brought it to you. On my boat.

54:23.000 --> 54:28.000
With these proud words, he gave Christopher Robin the message.

54:28.000 --> 54:32.000
But it's from Piglet, quite Christopher Robin, when he'd read it.

54:32.000 --> 54:38.000
Isn't there anything about Pooh in it? asked Bear, looking over his shoulder.

54:38.000 --> 54:41.000
Christopher Robin read the message aloud.

54:41.000 --> 54:47.000
Oh, are those peas, Piglets? I thought they were Pooh's.

54:47.000 --> 54:51.000
We must rescue him at once. I thought he was with you, Pooh.

54:51.000 --> 54:54.000
Owl, could you rescue him on your back?

54:54.000 --> 54:58.000
I don't think so, said Owl after grave thought.

54:58.000 --> 55:02.000
It is doubtful if the necessary dorsal muscles.

55:02.000 --> 55:06.000
Then would you fly to him at once and say that rescue is coming?

55:06.000 --> 55:09.000
And Pooh and I will think of a rescue and come as quick as ever we can.

55:09.000 --> 55:12.000
Oh, don't talk, Owl, go on quick!

55:12.000 --> 55:16.000
And still thinking of something to say, Owl flew off.

55:16.000 --> 55:19.000
Now then, Pooh, said Christopher Robin, where's your boat?

55:19.000 --> 55:26.000
I ought to say, explain Pooh, as they walk down to the shore of the island, that it isn't just an ordinary sort of boat.

55:26.000 --> 55:31.000
Sometimes it's a boat and sometimes it's more of an accident. It all depends.

55:31.000 --> 55:35.000
Depends on what, on whether I'm on the top of it or underneath it.

55:35.000 --> 55:43.000
Oh, well, where is it? There, said Pooh, pointing proudly to the floating bear.

55:43.000 --> 55:46.000
It wasn't what Christopher Robin expected.

55:46.000 --> 55:52.000
And the more he looked at it, the more he thought what a brave and clever bear Pooh was.

55:52.000 --> 56:02.000
And the more Christopher Robin thought this, the more Pooh looked modestly down his nose and tried to pretend he wasn't.

56:02.000 --> 56:06.000
But it's too small for two of us, said Christopher Robin sadly.

56:06.000 --> 56:11.000
Three of us with piglet. That makes it smaller still.

56:11.000 --> 56:14.000
Pooh bear, what shall we do?

56:14.000 --> 56:23.000
And then this bear, Pooh bear, Winnie the Pooh, F-O-P, friend of piglets.

56:23.000 --> 56:26.000
R-C, rabbit's companion.

56:26.000 --> 56:29.000
P-D, pole discoverer.

56:29.000 --> 56:34.000
E-C and T-F, Eor's comforter and tailfinder.

56:34.000 --> 56:43.000
In fact, Pooh himself said something so clever that Christopher Robin could only look at him with mouth, open and eyes staring.

56:43.000 --> 56:52.000
Wondering if this was really the bear of very little brain, whom he had known and loved so long.

56:52.000 --> 56:57.000
We might go in your umbrella, said Pooh.

56:57.000 --> 57:03.000
Hmm? We might go in your umbrella, said Pooh.

57:03.000 --> 57:04.000
Hmm?

57:04.000 --> 57:10.000
We might go in your umbrella, said Pooh.

57:11.000 --> 57:16.000
For suddenly Christopher Robin saw that they might.

57:16.000 --> 57:21.000
He opened his umbrella and put it point downwards in the water.

57:21.000 --> 57:25.000
It floated, but wobbled. Pooh got in.

57:25.000 --> 57:29.000
He was just beginning to say that it was alright now when he found that it wasn't.

57:29.000 --> 57:34.000
So, after a short drink, which he didn't really want, he waded back to Christopher Robin.

57:34.000 --> 57:39.000
Then they both got in together and it wobbled no longer.

57:39.000 --> 57:52.000
I shall call this boat the brain of Pooh, said Christopher Robin, and the brain of Pooh set sail forthwith in a southwesterly direction, revolving gracefully.

57:52.000 --> 57:57.000
You can imagine Piglet's joy when at last the ship came inside of him.

57:57.000 --> 58:04.000
In after years, he liked to think that he had been in very great danger during the terrible flood.

58:04.000 --> 58:09.000
But the only danger he had really been in was the last half hour of his imprisonment.

58:09.000 --> 58:19.000
When Owl, who had just flown up, sat on a branch of his tree to comfort him, and told him a very long story about an aunt who had once laid a seagulls egg by mistake.

58:19.000 --> 58:31.000
And the story went on and on rather like this sentence, until Piglet, who was listening out of his window without much hope, went to sleep quietly and naturally, slipping slowly out of the window towards the water,

58:31.000 --> 58:45.000
until he was only hanging on by his toes, at which moment luckily a sudden loud squawk from Owl, which was really part of the story, being what his aunt said, woke the Piglet up, and just gave him time to jerk himself back into safety and say,

58:45.000 --> 58:48.000
How interesting, and did she?

58:48.000 --> 59:03.000
When, well, you can imagine his joy when at last he saw the good ship, Brain of Pooh, Captain C. Robin, First Mate P. Bear, coming over the sea to rescue him.

59:03.000 --> 59:12.000
And as that is really the end of the story, and I am very tired after that last sentence, I think I shall stop there.

59:19.000 --> 59:26.000
Chapter 10, in which Christopher Robin gives a Pooh party, and we say goodbye.

59:28.000 --> 59:38.000
One day when the sun had come back over the forest, bringing with it the scent of May, and all the streams of the forest were tinkling happily to find themselves their own pretty shape again,

59:38.000 --> 59:46.000
and the little pools lay dreaming of the life they had seen and the big things they had done, and in the warmth and quiet of the forest,

59:46.000 --> 59:51.000
the cuckoo was trying over his voice carefully and listening to see if he liked it.

59:51.000 --> 01:00:00.000
And wood pigeons were complaining gently to themselves in their lazy, comfortable way that it was the other fellas' fault, but it didn't matter very much.

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:11.000
On such a day as this, Christopher Robin whistled in a special way he had, and Owl came flying out of the 100-acre wood to see what was wanted.

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:17.000
Owl, said Christopher Robin, I am going to give a party.

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:30.000
You are, are you, said Owl, and it's to be a special sort of party, because of what Pooh did when he did what he did to save Piglet from the flood.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:35.000
Oh, that's what it's for, is it, said Owl? Yes.

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:40.000
So will you tell Pooh as quickly as you can, and all the others, because it will be tomorrow?

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:45.000
Oh, it will, will it, said Owl, still being as helpful as possible.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:48.000
So will you go and tell them Owl?

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:55.000
Owl tried to think of something very wise to say, but couldn't, so he flew off to tell the others.

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:59.000
And the first person he told was Pooh.

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:04.000
Pooh, he said, Christopher Robin is giving a party.

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:07.000
Oh, said Pooh.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:16.000
And then seeing that Owl expected him to say something else, he said, will there be those little cake things with pink sugar icing?

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:24.000
Owl felt that it was rather beneath him to talk about little cake things with pink sugar icing, so he told Pooh exactly what Christopher Robin had said,

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:27.000
and flew off to Eor.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:33.000
A party, for me, thought Pooh to himself. How grand.

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:40.000
And he began to wonder if all the other animals would know that it was a special Pooh party.

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:48.000
And if Christopher Robin had told them about the floating bear and the brain of Pooh and all the wonderful ships he had invented and sailed on,

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:55.000
and he began to think how awful it would be if everybody had forgotten about it, and nobody quite knew what the party was for.

01:01:55.000 --> 01:02:02.000
And the more he thought like this, the more the party got muddled in his mind, like a dream when nothing goes right.

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:08.000
And the dream began to sing itself over in his head until it became a sort of song.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:13.000
It was an anxious Pooh song.

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:22.000
Three cheers for Pooh, for Pooh, for Pooh. Why, what did he do? I thought you knew. He saved his friend from a wedding.

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:30.000
Three cheers for bear, for where? For bear. He couldn't swim, but he rescued him. He rescued who?

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:40.000
Listen, do I am talking of Pooh, of Pooh. I'm sorry, I keep forgetting. Well, Pooh was a bear of enormous brain.

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:51.000
Just say it again. Of enormous brain. Of enormous what? Well, he ate a lot. And I don't know if he could swim or not, but he managed to float on a sort of boat.

01:02:51.000 --> 01:03:00.000
What a sort of what? Well, a sort of pot. So now let's give him three hearty cheers. So now let's give him three hearty witches.

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:10.000
And hope he'll be with us for years and years, and grow in health and wisdom and riches. Three cheers for Pooh, for Pooh, for Pooh.

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:17.000
Three cheers for bear, for where? For bear. Three cheers for the wonderful Willy the Pooh.

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:27.000
Just tell me somebody. What did he do? While this was going on inside him, Owl was talking to Eor.

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:32.000
Eor? said Owl. Christopher Robin is giving a party.

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:41.000
Very interesting, said Eor. I suppose they'll be sending me down the odd bits which got trodden on.

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:47.000
Kind and thoughtful, not at all. Don't mention it.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:57.000
There is an invitation for you. What's that like? An invitation? Yes, I heard you who dropped it.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:02.000
This isn't anything to eat. It's asking you to the party tomorrow.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:14.000
Eor shook his head slowly. You mean piglet? The little fell over the excited ears. That's piglet. I'll tell him.

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:21.000
No, no, said Owl, getting quite fussy. It's you. Are you sure?

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:30.000
Of course I'm sure. Christopher Robin said all of them. Tell all of them. All of them, except Eor.

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:34.000
All of them, said Owl, sulkyly.

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:47.000
Ah, said Eor. A mistake, no doubt. But still I shall come. Only don't blame me if it rains.

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:55.000
But it didn't rain. Christopher Robin had made a long table out of some long pieces of wood and they all sat round it.

01:04:55.000 --> 01:05:03.000
Christopher Robin sat at one end and poo sat at the other. And between them on one side were Owl and Eor and Piglet.

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:07.000
And between them on the other side were Rabbit and Rue and Canga.

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:17.000
And all Rabbit's friends and relations spread themselves about on the grass and waited hopefully in case anybody spoke to them or dropped anything or asked them the time.

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:25.000
It was the first party to which Rue had ever been and he was very excited. As soon as ever they had sat down he began to talk.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:29.000
Hello, Poo. He squeaked. Hello, Rue, said Poo.

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:33.000
Rue jumped up and down in his seat for a little while and then began again.

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:40.000
Hello, Piglet. He squeaked. Piglet waved a paw at him being too busy to say anything.

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:46.000
Hello, Eor. Said Rue. Eor nodded gloomily at him.

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:51.000
It will rain soon. You see if it doesn't, he said.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:56.000
Rue looked to see if it didn't and it didn't. So he said,

01:05:56.000 --> 01:05:59.000
Hello Owl. And Owl said,

01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:02.000
Hello, my little fellow, in a kindly way.

01:06:02.000 --> 01:06:09.000
I went on telling Christopher Robin about an accident which had nearly happened to a friend of his whom Christopher Robin didn't know.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:13.000
And Canga said to Rue, drink up your milk first year and talk afterwards.

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:23.000
So Rue who was drinking his milk tried to say that he could do both at once and had to be patted on the back and dried for quite a long time afterwards.

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:38.000
When they had all nearly eaten enough, Christopher Robin banged on the table with his spoon and everybody stopped talking and was very silent except Rue who was just finishing a loud attack of hiccups and trying to look as if it was one of rabbit's relations.

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:46.000
This party, said Christopher Robin, is a party because of what someone did.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:52.000
And we all know who it was and it's his party because of what he did.

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:56.000
And I've got a present for him and here it is.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:06:59.000
Then he felt about a little whispered,

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:01.000
Where is it?

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:07.000
While he was looking, Eor coughed in an impressive way and began to speak.

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:13.000
Friends, he said, including oddments.

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:23.000
It is a great pleasure or perhaps I'd better say it has been a pleasure so far to see you at my party.

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:26.000
What I did was nothing.

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:32.000
Any of you except rabbit and owl and Canga would have done the same.

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:34.000
Oh, and poo.

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:41.000
Murray Marx do not of course apply to piglet and room because they are too small.

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:47.000
Any of you would have done the same, but it just happened to be me.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:55.000
It was not I need hardly say with an idea of getting what Christopher Robin is looking for now.

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:59.000
And he put his front leg to his mouth and said in a loud whisper,

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:09.000
Try under the table that I did and what I did, but because I feel that we should all do what we can to help,

01:08:09.000 --> 01:08:13.000
I feel we should all.

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:15.000
Said Rue accidentally.

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:18.000
Rue, dear, said Canga, reproachfully.

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:20.000
Was it me?

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:22.000
Ask Rue a little surprised.

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:24.000
What's Eor talking about?

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:26.000
Piglet whispered to Pooh.

01:08:26.000 --> 01:08:29.000
I don't know, said Pooh, rather dolefully.

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:32.000
I thought this was your party.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:35.000
I thought it was once, but I suppose it isn't.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:38.000
I'd sooner it was yours than Eor's.

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:39.000
Said Piglet.

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:42.000
So would I, said Pooh.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:44.000
Look, said Rue again.

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:50.000
As I was saying, said Eor loudly and sternly,

01:08:50.000 --> 01:08:55.000
As I was saying when I was interrupted by various loud sounds,

01:08:55.000 --> 01:09:01.000
I feel that it is quite Christopher Robin excitedly.

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:03.000
Pass it down to Silio Pooh.

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:05.000
It's for Pooh.

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:07.000
For Pooh?

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:08.000
Said Eor.

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:09.000
Of course it is.

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:13.000
The best bear in all the world.

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:16.000
I might have known, said Eor.

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:19.000
After all, one can't complain.

01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:22.000
I have my friends.

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:26.000
Somebody spoke to me only yesterday.

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:29.000
And was it last week, or the week before,

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:32.000
That rabbit bumped into me and said,

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:36.000
Mother, the social round.

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:40.000
Oh, is something going on?

01:09:40.000 --> 01:09:41.000
Nobody was listening for.

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:43.000
They were all saying, open it Pooh.

01:09:43.000 --> 01:09:44.000
What is it Pooh?

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:45.000
I know what it is.

01:09:45.000 --> 01:09:46.000
No, you don't.

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:48.000
And other helpful remarks of this sort.

01:09:48.000 --> 01:09:51.000
Of course, Pooh was opening it as quickly as ever he could,

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:56.000
But without cutting the string because you never know when a bit of string might be useful.

01:09:56.000 --> 01:09:59.000
At last, it was undone.

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:03.000
When Pooh saw what it was, he nearly fell down.

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:05.000
He was so pleased.

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:08.000
It was a special pencil case.

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:12.000
There were pencils in it marked B for bear,

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:16.000
And pencils marked HB for helping bear,

01:10:16.000 --> 01:10:21.000
And pencils marked BB for brave bear.

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:24.000
There was a knife for sharpening the pencils,

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:27.000
And India rubber for rubbing out anything which you'd spelt wrong,

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:32.000
And a ruler for ruling lines for the words to walk on.

01:10:32.000 --> 01:10:36.000
And inches marked on the ruler in case you wanted to know how many inches anything was,

01:10:36.000 --> 01:10:38.000
And blue pencils, and red pencils,

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:43.000
And green pencils for saying special things in blue and red and green.

01:10:43.000 --> 01:10:47.000
And all these lovely things were in little pockets of their own,

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:51.000
In a special case which shut with a click when you clicked it.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:55.000
And they were all for Pooh.

01:10:55.000 --> 01:10:58.000
Oh, said Pooh.

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:01.000
Oh, Pooh!

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:04.000
Said everybody else, except Eor.

01:11:04.000 --> 01:11:08.000
Thank you, ground Pooh.

01:11:08.000 --> 01:11:11.000
But Eor was saying to himself,

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:16.000
This writing, business, pencils, and whatnot,

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:19.000
Overrated, if you ask me,

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:21.000
Silly stuff.

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:24.000
Nothing in it.

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:29.000
Later on, when it all said goodbye, and thank you to Christopher Robin,

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:34.000
Pooh and Piglet walked home thoughtfully together in the golden evening.

01:11:34.000 --> 01:11:39.000
And for a long time, they were silent.

01:11:39.000 --> 01:11:43.000
When you wake up in the morning, Pooh.

01:11:43.000 --> 01:11:46.000
Said Piglet, I'd last.

01:11:46.000 --> 01:11:49.000
What's the first thing you say to yourself?

01:11:49.000 --> 01:11:52.000
What's for breakfast, said Pooh?

01:11:52.000 --> 01:11:55.000
What do you say, Piglet?

01:11:55.000 --> 01:12:00.000
I say, I wonder what's going to happen, exciting today.

01:12:00.000 --> 01:12:02.000
Said Piglet.

01:12:02.000 --> 01:12:05.000
Pooh nodded thoughtfully.

01:12:05.000 --> 01:12:09.000
It's the same thing, he said.

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:13.000
And what did happen, asked Christopher Robin?

01:12:13.000 --> 01:12:15.000
When?

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:16.000
Next morning.

01:12:16.000 --> 01:12:18.000
I don't know.

01:12:18.000 --> 01:12:21.000
Could you think and tell me and Pooh sometime?

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:23.000
If you wanted it very much.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:27.000
Pooh does, said Christopher Robin.

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:32.000
He gave a deep sigh, picked his bear up by the leg and walked off to the door,

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:35.000
trailing Winnie the Pooh behind him.

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:37.000
At the door he turned and said,

01:12:37.000 --> 01:12:40.000
coming to see me have my bath?

01:12:40.000 --> 01:12:43.000
I might, I said.

01:12:43.000 --> 01:12:48.000
Was Pooh's pencil case any better than mine?

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:51.000
It was just the same, I said.

01:12:51.000 --> 01:12:54.000
He nodded and went out.

01:12:54.000 --> 01:13:01.000
And in a moment I heard Winnie the Pooh bump, bump, bump,

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:05.000
going up the stairs, behind him.

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:11.000
The end.

